Largest and widest street of Ancient Rome
Mar 2024 • Family
Via Sacra was the widest and main street in Ancient Rome, making its way from Capitoline Hill all the way to the Colosseum. Today, this street is paved, making it easy for walking, especially in the Roman Forum area where ground can be unstable in quite a few places.

If you walk Via Sacra, from the Colosseum, you will pass by the Arch of Titus. Shortly after, you will begin to experience building ruins on all sides of you, all the way to the Arch of Septimius Severus.

Do make sure to have a good travel guide or mobile application to help you understand what ruins are you looking at along Via Sacra. Otherwise, take lots of pictures and enjoy what you are seeing and experiencing in the heart of Ancient Rome.
Written June 3, 2024

Ancient Rome’s main street
Jan 2024 • Couples
Connecting Capitoline Hill to the Colosseum through the Roman Forum, Via Sacra has served as the main thoroughfare for the Romans for more than 20 centuries. Its name which means "Sacred Way" in English stems from its course through some of Ancient Rome's most important religious sites. As Ancient Rome's main street, you could almost visualise the many feet that have trodden this path over the centuries - from triumphal parades to celebrate a military victory to funeral processions for the emperors. It is also lined with the homes of Ancient Rome's wealthiest citizens, the ruins of which are still visible today. Its location within the Roman Forum means that visitors would need the 3-in-1 Colosseum, Roman Forum and Palatine Hills ticket for entry. The ruins worth taking note as you trod down this historic street include the Arch of Titus, Temple of Vestals, Curia and Temple of Saturn. Definitely a cherishable experience as it’s not everyday that you get to stroll down a street which has been in existence for 2 millenniums.
Written March 29, 2024

Temples, Triumphal Processions & Emperors’ Funerals
Jun 2022
Moseying down the Via Sacra, you can’t help but consider how many feet have trod this path before you. It’s the oldest street in Rome and was the main street connecting the top of Capitoline Hill to the Roman Forum.
It was not only ancient travellers and citizens who took this route.
Triumphal processions passed down the street, with victorious generals leading their armies to Jupiter’s Temple.
Funeral processions of emperors followed the same path. Richly dressed and with a death mask covering his face, the dead emperor’s body would be paraded into the Forum and then carried to Campus Martius.
What you see here today is mostly very well preserved. Large areas of the thick, black slabs of stone that made up the road are still intact. Time has worn them down to a smooth surface.
As you walk along, you pass by the ruins of many of ancient Rome’s most important buildings and religious temples - the Colosseum, the Arch of Titus, the Temple of Vestals, the Temple of Caesar, the Temple of Venus and Rome and the Saturn Temple.
However most of the Via Sacra lies within the grounds of the Roman Forum which means you’ll need to buy the combination Colosseum/Roman Forum ticket to access it.
Written March 20, 2023

Main Street, Ancient Rome
Feb 2020 • Solo
Amazing to see what still stands after more than 2,000 years. Located within the Roman Forum/Ancient Rome areas, this was the Main Street of Ancient Rome. It was along this street that festivals took place, business transpired (including prostitution), public trials took place, the public came to socialize, etc. Today, the stone street is remarkably well preserved as are some of the columns that lined the road. Only some parts can be accessed.
